At 10,659 as of yesterday. Our 7-day average has risen to 2,167. If we held that average, we'd break the 14K mark this week. I see that the crowd has moved significantly to the right on this prediction over the last 24 hours, and I'm tempted to as well given how high our peak was two days ago.

Covid deaths seem to have gone into decline beginning in early February and now remain in the 1,000 to 3,000 a day range (according to the CDC). It continues to spike from the low 1,000 range to the low 3,000 range which is why I can't be sure whether it will be less or more than 14,000. However, there would have to be a higher number of deaths the next few days for the count to be over 14,000, so I am more inclined to choose fewer than 14,000.

Though even without the anomaly this week would still be up a little over last, so if John Hopkins correctly dates those deaths and the 806 deaths from yesterday get moved (like they did with a previous reporting dump), it still looks like the question is likely to end at over 14k deaths.

Since my last forecast a week ago, the rate of decline has steadily risen (is that a double-negative?). Over the last 7 days, the weekly total has decreased between 2% and almost 4%. We were at 16.5K as of yesterday. We've seen *no* increases in over 2 weeks (since 1 FEB). If continued on a 3% decline through 28 FEB, we'd be looking at just over 11K for the week. If we should happen to level off, say to somewhere around 1%, we'd be looking at about 14.5K.

I agree with Ryan-Beck in expecting deaths to drop, relatively consistent with the sharp drop in cases since January 12. Note that the number of deaths reported over the past week has been inflated by Ohio's late reporting of 4,000 "overlooked" deaths from the past several months. This could happen again, of course, but if you take the seven-day average of 3,136 deaths, multiply it by 7 and deduct 4,000, you're at 17,952. If deaths go down by only 22%, you're at 14,000. Cases went down from January 12 to January 26 by 33%, and then by another 35% from January 26 to February 9--the slope has been pretty consistent.

For reference the most-recent (2/13/21) CDC 7-day moving average for U.S. deaths was 3,136 per day. (I.e., remaining above 3,000/day.) This includes a 'spike' of 5500+ reported deaths on 2/12/21. (https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/#trends_dailytrendscases)

I generally agree with the thoughtful analysis by @Redcayenne . However, I think the effects of the vaccine are just too early to consider. See this report about the effects of vaccination rates in Israel. https://ourworldindata.org/vaccination-israel-impact. There 40% have at least one dose and 25% are fully vaccinated. New cases started dropping on Jan 15 when 25% had one dose (80% for those over 60) and 4% were fully vaccinated. Even then, the drop was relatively modest.

Based on a 14+ day lag in deaths following confirmed cases, the deaths during the week starting on Feb 21st will correspond to 1.5-1.7% of confirmed cases from the week 7-13 Feb. Confirmed cases from 7th to 9th is 117276 + 110853 + 108128. Assuming roughly the same trajectory, the remaining 4 days would total 335k confirmed cases. All of these combined gives 670k cases.
